{{ pov_hint }}
Shape everything you decide to SERVE that scheme (a rotating-viewpoint story
needs a cast whose members can carry chapters; a journal-interlude scheme needs
a character positioned to write one). Never restate it as a different scheme.
{% endif %}

Every later stage will be held to this contract, so be specific and opinionated:
"windswept, intimate, slow-burning" is a tone; "atmospheric" is not.

A vision states texture and intent, not inventory. You cannot know yet how many
suspects, motives, or subplots the structure will hold, so never promise
countable coverage ("every X carries a Y") — later stages would be held to
arithmetic no vision can see. Say what the story must FEEL like when it commits
fully; let the structural stages decide what exists.
